    <section>
      <h2>What Is a Robo-Advisor?</h2>
      <p>A <strong>robo-advisor</strong> is an online investment platform that uses computer algorithms to build and manage a diversified investment portfolio on your behalf. When you sign up, you answer a questionnaire about your financial goals, time horizon, and risk tolerance. The platform then creates a portfolio &mdash; typically composed of low-cost exchange-traded funds (ETFs) &mdash; tailored to your profile.</p>
      <p>Once your portfolio is established, the robo-advisor continuously monitors it and automatically rebalances when your allocations drift from their targets. Many also perform tax-loss harvesting, a strategy that sells losing investments to offset taxable gains and reduce your tax bill. All of this happens without you needing to make a single trade or monitor the markets.</p>
      <p>Robo-advisors emerged in the aftermath of the 2008 financial crisis, with Betterment and Wealthfront launching in 2010 and 2011 respectively. Since then, virtually every major brokerage &mdash; including Vanguard, Schwab, and Fidelity &mdash; has launched its own robo-advisory service. The industry now manages over $1.5 trillion in assets globally.</p>
