    <section>
      <h2>Detailed Provider Reviews</h2>

      <h3>Betterment &mdash; Best All-Around Robo-Advisor</h3>
      <p>Betterment is the largest independent robo-advisor with over $45 billion in assets under management. Its 0.25 percent annual fee provides automatic rebalancing, tax-loss harvesting, dividend reinvestment, and goal-based portfolio allocation. You can open multiple goals (retirement, emergency fund, house down payment) each with a different risk level, and Betterment will manage them independently.</p>
      <p>The platform offers a range of portfolio strategies including a core broad-market portfolio, a socially responsible investing (SRI) portfolio, a Goldman Sachs Smart Beta portfolio, and an income-focused portfolio. Tax-loss harvesting is included at all balance levels, which is a significant advantage over competitors that restrict it to higher balances.</p>
      <p>Betterment Premium, at 0.65 percent annually, adds unlimited access to certified financial planners via phone or video. For investors who want the convenience of a robo-advisor but occasionally need human guidance, Premium offers a strong middle ground between pure automation and a traditional advisor.</p>

      <h3>Wealthfront &mdash; Best for Tax Optimization</h3>
      <p>Wealthfront manages over $70 billion in assets and has built its reputation on sophisticated tax optimization. Its standard tax-loss harvesting operates daily, scanning for opportunities more frequently than most competitors. For accounts above $100,000, Wealthfront offers <strong>direct indexing</strong>, which owns individual stocks instead of an ETF to harvest losses at the individual stock level &mdash; a strategy that can add 1 to 2 percent in after-tax returns annually.</p>
      <p>Wealthfront also includes a financial planning tool called Path that integrates with your external accounts to provide projections for retirement, home buying, college savings, and more. The platform requires a $500 minimum to start investing but charges the same 0.25 percent annual fee as Betterment.</p>
      <p>One limitation is that Wealthfront does not offer access to human financial advisors at any tier, making it a purely automated solution. For investors comfortable with a fully digital experience who prioritize tax efficiency, Wealthfront is difficult to beat.</p>

      <h3>Vanguard Digital Advisor &mdash; Best for Low Expense Ratios</h3>
      <p>Vanguard Digital Advisor combines Vanguard's legendary low-cost index funds with automated portfolio management. The net advisory fee is approximately 0.20 percent (after accounting for the revenue Vanguard earns from the underlying funds), making it one of the cheapest options available. The catch is a $3,000 minimum investment, which is higher than most competitors.</p>
      <p>Portfolios are built exclusively with Vanguard funds, which have some of the lowest expense ratios in the industry. The platform includes automatic rebalancing and a MinTax feature that applies tax-efficient strategies to your account. If you want human advisor access, you can upgrade to Vanguard Personal Advisor at 0.30 percent annually with a $50,000 minimum.</p>

      <h3>Schwab Intelligent Portfolios &mdash; Best Zero-Fee Option</h3>
      <p>Schwab Intelligent Portfolios charges no advisory fee whatsoever, making it technically the cheapest robo-advisor available. However, the platform requires a relatively high cash allocation (typically 6 to 10 percent of your portfolio) held in a Schwab cash account, on which Schwab earns interest income. This cash drag can reduce your overall returns by 0.15 to 0.30 percent annually compared to being fully invested, partially offsetting the zero-fee advantage.</p>
      <p>Tax-loss harvesting is available for accounts above $50,000. The Premium tier adds unlimited access to a certified financial planner for $30 per month (after a $300 one-time setup fee). For existing Schwab clients or investors with larger balances where the cash drag is proportionally smaller, Intelligent Portfolios is an excellent choice.</p>

      <h3>Fidelity Go &mdash; Best for Small Balances</h3>
      <p>Fidelity Go stands out with its fee structure for smaller accounts: there is no advisory fee at all on balances under $25,000. This makes it an ideal starting point for new investors who are just beginning to build their portfolios. Above $25,000, the fee is 0.35 percent annually, which includes access to one-on-one coaching with Fidelity financial advisors.</p>
      <p>Fidelity Go invests in Fidelity Flex mutual funds, which have zero expense ratios. Combined with the zero advisory fee for small accounts, this means investors with under $25,000 pay literally nothing in management fees. The platform does not offer tax-loss harvesting, which is its primary limitation compared to Betterment and Wealthfront.</p>

      <h3>SoFi Automated Investing &mdash; Best Free Robo with Advisor Access</h3>
      <p>SoFi charges no management fee and provides free access to certified financial planners, making it one of the most generous offerings for cost-conscious beginners. The $1 minimum means virtually anyone can get started. Portfolios are built from SoFi-branded and third-party ETFs, with automatic rebalancing included.</p>
      <p>The trade-off is that SoFi does not offer tax-loss harvesting, and its ETF selection is more limited than what Betterment or Wealthfront provide. SoFi works best as part of the broader SoFi ecosystem (banking, loans, credit cards), where members earn additional perks. For someone starting out who wants zero fees and occasional human guidance, SoFi is a compelling option.</p>

      <h3>Ellevest &mdash; Best for Women-Focused Planning</h3>
      <p>Ellevest was founded specifically to address the gender investing gap. The platform incorporates gender-specific salary curves, longer life expectancies, and career breaks into its financial projections, providing more accurate planning for women. Membership-based pricing ($12 per month or $97 per year) includes investing, banking, retirement planning, and career coaching.</p>
      <p>The Plus tier adds tax-loss harvesting and one-on-one coaching sessions. While anyone can use Ellevest, its planning algorithms and content are particularly valuable for women who want financial projections that reflect their actual career and life patterns rather than generic assumptions.</p>

      <h3>M1 Finance &mdash; Best for Customizable Portfolios</h3>
      <p>M1 Finance is a hybrid between a robo-advisor and a self-directed brokerage. You build your own portfolio (called a "pie") by selecting individual stocks and ETFs and assigning target percentages. M1 then automatically rebalances your pie and reinvests dividends. There is no advisory fee.</p>
      <p>This makes M1 ideal for investors who want the automation of a robo-advisor but want full control over what they invest in. You can use M1's pre-built expert pies or create entirely custom allocations. The $100 minimum is reasonable, and the platform supports fractional shares. The main limitation is no tax-loss harvesting and no human advisor access.</p>
