      <p>For most people with straightforward financial needs &mdash; saving for retirement, building an emergency fund, investing for a future home &mdash; a robo-advisor provides everything needed at a fraction of the cost. Human advisors become more valuable when you have complex tax situations, business ownership, stock options, estate planning needs, or assets above $1 million where holistic financial planning provides significant value.</p>
      <p>Many investors use a hybrid approach: a robo-advisor handles day-to-day portfolio management while a fee-only financial planner (typically charging a flat fee of $1,000 to $3,000 per session) provides comprehensive advice once or twice per year.</p>
